==English==
===Etymology===
Latin ''[[abjurare]]'' to deny upon oath; ''[[ab]]'' + ''[[jurare]]'' to [[swear]], from ''[[jus]]'', ''[[juris]]'', right, law; cf. French ''[[abjurer]]''. See [[jury]]

===Pronunciation===
* ([[RP]]) {{IPA| /əbˈdʒʊə/}}

===Verb===
{{en-infl-reg-other-e|abjur|e|}}
# {{transitive}} To [[renounce]] upon [[oath]]; to [[forswear]]; to [[disavow]]; as, to '''abjure''' [[allegiance]] to a prince. ''To abjure the realm'', is to swear to abandon it [[forever]].
# {{transitive}} To renounce or [[reject]] with [[solemnity]]; to [[recant]]; to abandon [[forever]]; to reject; [[repudiate]]; as, to ''abjure'' errors.
#:*But this rough magic I here ''abjure''. - Shakespeare, ''Tempest, V,i''
# {{intransitive}} To renounce on oath. - Bishop Burnet

